What is Load Balancing?
Load balancing means spreading incoming user requests across multiple servers so that no single server gets overloaded.

Simple idea:
Instead of sending all traffic to one server, we distribute it smartly across many.

Real-Life Analogy
Imagine a busy fast-food restaurant:
	• 1 cashier → long lines, slow service  
	• 5 cashiers → faster service, happy customers 

Load balancer = manager assigning customers to different cashiers

How It Works
	1. User sends a request (opens your app/website) 
	2. Request first goes to a Load Balancer 
	3. Load balancer decides which server should handle it 
	4. Request is forwarded to that server 
	5. Server sends response back to user 

Why Load Balancing is Important
 1. High Availability
  If one server fails → traffic shifts to others
  Your app stays online
 
2. Scalability
You can add more servers as traffic grows
Supports millions of users

3. Better Performance
No single server is overloaded
aster response times

4. Fault Tolerance
Unhealthy servers are automatically avoided

Load Balancing Algorithms

Round Robin
Requests go one by one to each server, Simple but not always efficient

Least Connections
Send traffic to server with least active users, More balanced and smart

IP Hash
Same user → same server, Useful for login/session-based apps

Weighted
Powerful servers get more traffic, Optimized performance

Types of Load Balancers
 Layer 4 (Transport Layer)
	• Works on IP + Port 
	• Fast but basic 

Layer 7 (Application Layer)
	• Works on HTTP/HTTPS 
	• Can route based on: 
		○ URL 
		○ Headers 
		○ Cookies 
Example: /api → backend servers, /images → CDN

Real-World Example
Think about apps like Netflix or YouTube:
	• Millions of users watching videos 
	• Load balancer distributes traffic across thousands of servers
 That’s why streaming feels smooth 
